english:
  title: A Refutation of Buddhist Doctrines of Hell
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: "The ancient scholars have refuted the Buddhist teaching of hell, saying: \"The common people are deceived by the Buddhist priests. Whenever death occurs, they make offerings to the Buddha and feed the monks, claiming this will erase the sins of the deceased and secure them blessings, so they may be reborn in heaven to enjoy endless pleasures. Those who do not perform such rites must surely fall into hell, where they will be flayed, burned, ground, and crushed, suffering terrible torments. Yet this is utterly without reason. When the body decays and returns to dust, and the spirit scatters like mist, what form remains to be flayed or burned or ground? Moreover, before Buddhist teachings entered China, there were those who returned from death. Why then has not a single soul ever testified to falling into hell or beholding the so-called Ten Kings? This proves their doctrine false and unworthy of belief.\"\n\nSome say that the Buddhist hell-doctrine was merely created to frighten common people into virtue. Yet the Master Cheng said: \"Even though utmost sincerity can move heaven and earth, people are still not transformed. How could mere teaching transform them?\" \n\nOnce a monk asked me: \"If there is no hell, what fear would prevent men from doing evil?\" I replied: \"The gentleman loves goodness as he loves beauty, and hates evil as he hates foul odor—both arise naturally from the heart without calculation. When an evil name befalls a man, shame strikes his heart like the lash in the marketplace. Why should he need the doctrine of hell to refrain from wrongdoing?\" The monk fell silent. I record this exchange now so that those in the world confused by such teachings might learn to distinguish truth from falsehood."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '浮屠 (fu-tu): A transliteration of ''Buddha'' in Classical Chinese, used here to refer to Buddhist priests.'
  - key: ''
    value: '十王 (ten kings): In Buddhist cosmology, the Ten Kings of Hell who judge the dead and determine their karmic punishment.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Program子 (Cheng Zi): Likely referring to Cheng Yi or Cheng Hao, influential Neo-Confucian philosophers whose thought profoundly influenced Korean scholars like Jeong Do-jeon.'
